                  <rect x="1" y="1" width="14" height="14" rx="3" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <span>Biological consequences of failure explained (why hyperglycaemia/hypoglycaemia is dangerous)</span>
              </li>
              <li>
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <rect x="1" y="1" width="14" height="14" rx="3" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <span>Links between concepts made explicit (e.g. insulin resistance leads to elevated blood glucose because GLUT4 is not translocated)</span>
              </li>
              <li>
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <rect x="1" y="1" width="14" height="14" rx="3" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <span>Discussion of how the homeostatic mechanism maintains a stable internal environment overall (big picture)</span>
              </li>
              <li>
                <svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <rect x="1" y="1" width="14" height="14" rx="3" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <span>Clear, logical structure with accurate use of biological terminology throughout</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Merit / Excellence Tips
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="merit-tips" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Tips for Merit and Excellence</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            The difference between grade levels comes down to <strong>depth</strong> and
            <strong>integration</strong>. Here is what the markers are looking for at each level.
          </p>

          <div class="grade-tips">
            <!-- Merit tips -->
            <div class="grade-card grade-card--merit">
              <div class="grade-card__header">
                <h3>Merit</h3>
                <span class="grade-card__label">In-depth explanation</span>
              </div>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>
                  Explain <em>how</em> and <em>why</em> at each step — do not just name the
                  hormones, describe what they actually do at the cellular level
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use correct terminology: say "beta cells in the islets of Langerhans detect
                  elevated blood glucose" rather than "the pancreas senses sugar"
                </li>
                <li>
                  Include the signal transduction pathway: insulin binds to receptor, triggers
                  phosphorylation cascade, GLUT4 vesicles move to plasma membrane
                </li>
                <li>
                  Describe the liver's role explicitly: glycogenesis (glucose to glycogen) and
                  glycogenolysis (glycogen to glucose) — and when each occurs
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <!-- Excellence tips -->
            <div class="grade-card grade-card--excellence">
              <div class="grade-card__header">
                <h3>Excellence</h3>
                <span class="grade-card__label">Comprehensive, integrated discussion</span>
              </div>
              <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>
                  Connect the mechanism to its <strong>biological significance</strong> — explain
                  why the brain's dependence on glucose makes hypoglycaemia immediately dangerous,
                  while glycation explains the slow damage of chronic hyperglycaemia
                </li>
                <li>
                  Show how the <strong>whole system works together</strong> — antagonistic hormones,
                  multiple effectors (liver, muscle, fat cells), and feedback that adjusts
                  continuously, not just "on" or "off"
                </li>
                <li>
                  When discussing diabetes, explain the <strong>mechanism of disruption</strong> —
                  not just "insulin does not work" but why (autoimmune destruction of beta cells
                  for Type 1; insulin receptor down-regulation for Type 2)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Write with a clear, logical flow — the reader should be able to follow your
                  argument from stimulus to response to feedback without getting lost
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h4>
            <p>
              <strong>Naming without explaining:</strong> Saying "insulin lowers blood glucose"
              is Achieved-level. Explaining <em>how</em> insulin lowers blood glucose (receptor
              binding, signal cascade, GLUT4 translocation, facilitated diffusion into cells)
              is Merit-level. Explaining <em>why this matters</em> for the organism is Excellence.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Writing Tip</h4>
            <p>
              Use a diagram or flow chart if it helps you organise your ideas — but your written
              explanation should stand on its own. The marker needs to see your understanding
              in your words, not just in a labelled picture.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Lesson 3: Our Planet — Animal Behaviours
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="lesson-3" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <nav class="lesson-inline-nav" aria-label="Lesson navigation">
            <a href="#lesson-1-2" class="lesson-inline-nav__link lesson-inline-nav__link--prev">
              <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M13 8H3M7 4L3 8l4 4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
              Lessons 1–2: Dry Run
            </a>
            <span class="lesson-inline-nav__current">Lesson 3 of 3</span>
          </nav>

          <h2>Lesson 3: Our Planet — Animal Behaviour Observations</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Time for a change of pace. Today we are watching <strong>Our Planet</strong>,
            Season 1, Episode 3 — narrated by Sir David Attenborough. But this is not just
            passive viewing. Your task is to identify and classify the animal behaviours you
            observe, linking them back to the concepts from <strong>AS 91603</strong> (responses
            of plants and animals to their external environment).
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Netflix:</strong> Our Planet, Season 1, Episode 3 — <em>"Jungles"</em>.
              If you want to rewatch at home, it is available on Netflix. The full series is
              excellent revision material for animal behaviour and ecology.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── What to Watch For ── -->
          <h3>What to Watch For</h3>

          <p>
            As you watch, keep an eye out for examples of the following types of behaviour.
            These are all concepts you will need for AS 91603, so start building your bank
            of real-world examples now.
          </p>

          <div class="behaviour-categories">
            <div class="behaviour-card">
              <div class="behaviour-card__header">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="8" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                  <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="3" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Innate Behaviours</h4>
              </div>
              <p>
                Genetically programmed, no learning required. Present from birth. Look for
                instinctive responses — feeding patterns, reflexes, courtship displays that
                are species-wide.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="behaviour-card">
              <div class="behaviour-card__header">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M4 19.5A2.5 2.5 0 016.5 17H20" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <path d="M6.5 2H20v20H6.5A2.5 2.5 0 014 19.5v-15A2.5 2.5 0 016.5 2z" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Learned Behaviours</h4>
              </div>
              <p>
                Modified by experience. Includes habituation, classical conditioning, operant
                conditioning, and imprinting. Watch for animals that adapt their behaviour
                based on past experience.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="behaviour-card">
              <div class="behaviour-card__header">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M5 12h14M12 5l7 7-7 7" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Taxis &amp; Kinesis</h4>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Taxis:</strong> directional movement toward or away from a stimulus
                (phototaxis, chemotaxis). <strong>Kinesis:</strong> non-directional change in
                speed or turning rate in response to a stimulus.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="behaviour-card">
              <div class="behaviour-card__header">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M21 15a2 2 0 01-2 2H7l-4 4V5a2 2 0 012-2h14a2 2 0 012 2v10z" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Communication</h4>
              </div>
              <p>
                Visual, auditory, chemical (pheromones), or tactile signals between organisms.
                Watch for mating calls, warning displays, territorial markings, or cooperative
                signalling.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="behaviour-card">
              <div class="behaviour-card__header">
                <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M12 2L2 21h20L12 2z" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                  <path d="M12 9v4M12 16v.5" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Predator–Prey Responses</h4>
              </div>
              <p>
                Predator strategies (ambush, pursuit, cooperative hunting) and prey defences
                (camouflage, mimicry, alarm calls, flight responses, playing dead). These are
                rich examples for AS 91603.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


